---
import DocLayout from "../layouts/DocLayout.astro";
import "../styles/Global.css";
---

<DocLayout title="Introduction">
    <section id="introduction">
        <h1 class="docs-title">Introduction</h1>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="what-is-astroanimate">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">What is AstroAnimate?</h2>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">
                AstroAnimate is an <span class="docs-para-highlight"
                    >Astro animation library</span
                > designed for adding animations to Astro components without requiring
                runtime JavaScript by default.
            </p>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">It focuses on:</p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>
                    Component-level animations (entry, reveal, transitions, and
                    rotating text state changes)
                </li>
                <li>Performance-first implementation using CSS</li>
                <li>
                    Compatibility with Astro’s rendering model (SSR + islands)
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">
                Unlike traditional animation libraries that rely heavily on
                JavaScript,<span class="docs-para-highlight">
                    AstroAnimate uses CSS-driven animations as the default</span
                >, with optional JavaScript enhancements when needed.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="what-youll-achieve">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">What You'll Achieve</h2>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">By the end of this page, you will:</p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>Understand what AstroAnimate is and how it works</li>
                <li>Know when it fits your project</li>
                <li>See how it differs from traditional animation libraries</li>
                <li>Decide whether to install it in your Astro project</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="why-astroanimate-exists">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">Why AstroAnimate Exists</h2>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">
                Animating UI in Astro often involves trade-offs:
            </p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>Adding JavaScript for simple animations</li>
                <li>Mixing multiple libraries (CSS + JS + frameworks)</li>
                <li>Losing performance benefits of Astro</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">
                AstroAnimate is designed to reduce that friction by providing:
            </p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>A consistent animation API for Astro components</li>
                <li>
                    A CSS-first approach with optional JavaScript enhancements
                </li>
                <li>Pre-built, reusable animation primitives</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="what-problem-does-it-solve">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">What Problem Does It Solve?</h2>

            <div class="comparison-section">
                <!-- WITHOUT -->
                <div class="comparison-group">
                    <h3 class="comparison-title">Without AstroAnimate</h3>
                    <ul class="comparison-list">
                        <li>
                            <img src="/images/icon-cross-rounded.png" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="20" height="20" />
                            <span
                                >You write custom CSS animations repeatedly</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <img src="/images/icon-cross-rounded.png" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="20" height="20" />
                            <span
                                >You integrate external libraries (GSAP, Motion)
                                for simple effects</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <img src="/images/icon-cross-rounded.png" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="20" height="20" />
                            <span>You manage performance manually</span>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <!-- WITH -->
                <div class="comparison-group">
                    <h3 class="comparison-title">With AstroAnimate</h3>
                    <ul class="comparison-list">
                        <li>
                            <img src="/images/icon-check-rounded.png" alt="" width="20" height="20" />
                            <span
                                >You use ready-to-use animation components</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <img src="/images/icon-check-rounded.png" alt="" width="20" height="20" />
                            <span>You keep JavaScript minimal or optional</span>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <img src="/images/icon-check-rounded.png" alt="" width="20" height="20" />
                            <span
                                >You follow a consistent pattern across your
                                project</span
                            >
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="when-to-use-astroanimate">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">When to Use AstroAnimate</h2>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">AstroAnimate works best for:</p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>Component animations (fade, slide, scale)</li>
                <li>Page transitions in Astro projects</li>
                <li>UI micro-interactions (hover, reveal, entry effects)</li>
                <li>
                    <span class="docs-para-highlight"
                        >Performance-sensitive websites (Landing pages, Blogs,
                        SaaS)</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="when-not-to-use-astroanimate">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">When NOT to Use AstroAnimate</h2>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">AstroAnimate is not designed for:</p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>Complex animation timelines</li>
                <li>Physics-based motion systems</li>
                <li>Advanced sequencing or choreography</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">For those use cases, consider:</p>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>GSAP</li>
                <li>Motion Libraries</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="info-alert">
                <div class="info-icon">🚀</div>
                <p>
                    AstroAnimate works side-by-side with GSAP and Three.js if
                    you need high-end complex animations.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="how-astroanimate-works">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">How AstroAnimate Works</h2>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">AstroAnimate is not designed for:</p>
            <div class="steps-list">
                <div class="step-item">
                    <h3>1. CSS-First Animations</h3>
                    <ul class="docs-list">
                        <li>
                            Uses <code class="docs-code">@keyframes</code>
                            and CSS properties
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            No runtime JavaScript required for baseline
                            animations
                        </li>
                        <li>Works with Astro SSR out of the box</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="step-item">
                    <h3>2. Optional JavaScript Enhancements</h3>
                    <ul class="docs-list">
                        <li>
                            For advanced use cases (scroll triggers,
                            interactions)
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Loaded only when needed (progressive enhancement)
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="step-item">
                    <h3>3. Native Astro Integration</h3>
                    <ul class="docs-list">
                        <li>
                            Works directly inside <code class="docs-code"
                                >.astro</code
                            > components
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Designed to work directly inside Astro components
                            and SSR rendering patterns.
                        </li>
                        <li>Supports island architecture</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="example">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">Example (What It Looks Like)</h2>
            <div class="docs-code-block">
                <pre><code><span class="comment">---</span>
<span class="keyword">import</span> <span class="component-name">FadeIn</span> <span class="keyword">from</span> <span class="string">"@astroanimate/core/FadeIn"</span>;
<span class="comment">---</span>

&lt;<span class="component">FadeIn</span>&gt;
    &lt;<span class="tag">h1</span>&gt;Hello AstroAnimate&lt;/<span class="tag">h1</span>&gt;
&lt;/<span class="component">FadeIn</span>&gt;</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">
                This applies a fade-in animation without adding runtime
                JavaScript.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="what-makes-astroanimate-different">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">What Makes AstroAnimate Different</h2>
            <div class="table-wrapper">
                <table class="docs-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Feature</th>
                            <th>AstroAnimate</th>
                            <th>Traditional Libraries</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Default behavior</td>
                            <td>CSS-based</td>
                            <td class="status-error">JavaScript-heavy</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Performance</td>
                            <td class="status-success">High (no runtime JS)</td>
                            <td class="status-error">Depends on usage</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Astro integration</td>
                            <td class="status-warning">Native</td>
                            <td class="status-error">Requires setup</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Use case</td>
                            <td>UI animations</td>
                            <td>Full animation systems</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
            <p class="docs-paragraph">
                This applies a fade-in animation without adding runtime
                JavaScript.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="notes-caveats">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">Notes / Caveats</h2>
            <ul class="docs-list">
                <li>
                    AstroAnimate prioritizes <span class="docs-para-highlight"
                        >simplicity and performance</span
                    > over complexity
                </li>
                <li>
                    Advanced animation scenarios may require external libraries
                </li>
                <li>
                    Some features depend on browser support for CSS animations
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="related-resources">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">Related Resources</h2>
            <ul class="docs-list docs-list-links">
                <li>→ /docs/installation/</li>
                <li>→ /docs/quick-start/</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-intro-section" id="faq">
            <h2 class="docs-subtitle">FAQ (Developer Questions)</h2>
            <div class="faq-container">
                <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary
                        >Is AstroAnimate only for Astro? <svg
                            class="chevron"
                            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                            fill="none"
                            stroke="currentColor"
                            stroke-width="2"
                            ><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline></svg
                        ></summary
                    >
                    <div class="faq-content">
                        Yes. AstroAnimate is built specifically for the Astro
                        framework and is optimized for its rendering model.
                    </div>
                </details>
                <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary
                        >Is AstroAnimate safe for SEO? <svg
                            class="chevron"
                            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                            fill="none"
                            stroke="currentColor"
                            stroke-width="2"
                            ><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline></svg
                        ></summary
                    >
                    <div class="faq-content">
                        Yes, because it's CSS-based, search engines can see all
                        content immediately without executing JS.
                    </div>
                </details>
                <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary
                        >Do I need JavaScript to use AstroAnimate? <svg
                            class="chevron"
                            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                            fill="none"
                            stroke="currentColor"
                            stroke-width="2"
                            ><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline></svg
                        ></summary
                    >
                    <div class="faq-content">
                        No. Most animations work using CSS only. JavaScript is
                        optional for advanced use cases.
                    </div>
                </details>
                <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary
                        >Is AstroAnimate production-ready? <svg
                            class="chevron"
                            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                            fill="none"
                            stroke="currentColor"
                            stroke-width="2"
                            ><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline></svg
                        ></summary
                    >
                    <div class="faq-content">
                        Yes, AstroAnimate is suitable for UI animations covered
                        by current components. Validate in your project
                        environment and use quality checks before production
                        rollout.
                    </div>
                </details>
                <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary
                        >Can I combine AstroAnimate with GSAP or Motion? <svg
                            class="chevron"
                            viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                            fill="none"
                            stroke="currentColor"
                            stroke-width="2"
                            ><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"></polyline></svg
                        ></summary
                    >
                    <div class="faq-content">
                        Yes. AstroAnimate can be used alongside other animation
                        libraries when needed.
                    </div>
                </details>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="docs-footer-nav">
            <a href="/docs/installation" class="next-link">
                <span class="label">NEXT</span>
                <span class="title"
                    >Installation <svg
                        width="18"
                        height="18"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="none"
                        stroke="currentColor"
                        stroke-width="2"
                        stroke-linecap="round"
                        stroke-linejoin="round"
                        ><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline
                            points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg
                    ></span
                >
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <Fragment slot="toc">
        <div class="toc-header">IN THIS PAGE</div>
        <nav class="toc-nav">
            <a href="#what-is-astroanimate" class="active"
                >What is AstroAnimate?</a
            >
            <a href="#what-youll-achieve">What You'll Achieve</a>
            <a href="#why-astroanimate-exists">Why AstroAnimate Exists</a>
            <a href="#what-problem-does-it-solve">What Problem Does It Solve?</a
            >
            <a href="#when-to-use-astroanimate">When to Use AstroAnimate</a>
            <a href="#when-not-to-use-astroanimate"
                >When NOT to Use AstroAnimate</a
            >
            <a href="#how-astroanimate-works">How AstroAnimate Works</a>
            <a href="#example">Example (What It Looks Like)</a>
            <a href="#what-makes-astroanimate-different"
                >What Makes AstroAnimate Different</a
            >
            <a href="#notes-caveats">Notes / Caveats</a>
            <a href="#related-resources">Related Resources</a>
            <a href="#faq">FAQ</a>
        </nav>
    </Fragment>
</DocLayout>
